  "prompt": "What is the difference between a royalty and a license?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of the key differences between royalties and licenses:\n\nRoyalty:\n1. A payment made to an owner for the use of their intellectual property\n2. Typically calculated as a percentage of revenue or per unit sold\n3. Ongoing payment for continued use of the property\n4. Common in music, patents, and publishing\n5. Represents compensation for the ongoing use of an asset\n\nLicense:\n1. A legal permission or agreement to use something owned by another party\n2. Grants specific rights to use intellectual property or other assets\n3. Can be for a fixed term or perpetual\n4. May involve an upfront fee or ongoing payments\n5. Defines the terms and conditions of use\n\nKey distinctions:\n- A license is the legal permission to use something\n- A royalty is the payment made for that use\n- A license can include royalty terms, but not all licenses involve royalties\n- Royalties are a form of compensation within a licensing agreement\n\nExample:\nA musician (licensor) might grant a record label (licensee) a license to distribute their music, with royalties paid based on album sales.",
